https://codeforces.com/problemset/problem/1890/A

A good array needs all adjacent sums to be equal.
From this, we get the rule: b[i] = b[i+2].
So all elements at odd positions are the same, and all at even positions are the same.
Hence, the array can contain at most two distinct values.
If there is only one value, it always works.
If there are two values, they must be placed alternately.
Alternation is possible only when their frequencies differ by at most 1.
If the frequency difference is more than 1, same values become adjacent.
More than two distinct values can never satisfy the condition.



Problem Link :https://codeforces.com/problemset/problem/1834/A

we first read the length of the array and its elements. We count how many -1 values are present and also calculate the total sum of the array. We keep a variable to store the number of operations performed. Since the product of the array is 1 only when the number of -1 elements is even, we first check this condition. If the count of -1 is odd, we flip one -1 to 1, increase the sum by 2, and increment the operation count by 1. After fixing the product condition, we check the sum of the array. If the sum is still negative, we repeatedly flip -1 elements to 1, each time increasing the sum by 2 and counting one operation, until the sum becomes non-negative. Finally, the total number of operations performed is the minimum number required to make the array good, and we output this value.
